  <p> We can now include the 2-qubit gates we've learned, <c>SWAP</c> and <c>CNOT</c>:</p>

  <listing xml:id="swap-and-cnot-gates">
    <title><c>SWAP</c> and <c>CNOT</c> Gate in Qiskit</title>
    <program xml:id="swap-and-cnot-gates-program" interactive="activecode" language="python3">
      <code>
        from qiskit import QuantumCircuit

        circuit2 = QuantumCircuit(3)
        circuit2.x(0)
        circuit2.swap(0, 1)
        circuit2.cx(1, 2)

        print(circuit2.draw())
      </code>
    </program>
  </listing>

  <p>The <c>swap(i, j)</c> function is pretty straightforward <mdash /> it just swaps the values of the qubits
    at indices <c>i</c> and <c>j</c>. Let's look closely at the CNOT gate in Qiskit:</p>

  <program language="python3">
    circuit2.cx(1, 2)
  </program>

  <p>First of all, similar to the <c>NOT</c> gate from before, the <c>CNOT</c> gate is called <c>cx</c>,
    meaning <term>controlled-X</term>, in Qiskit. Secondly, the <em>order of parameters</em> for the <c>cx(i, j)</c>
    function is crucial: the first parameter (<c>i</c>) represents the index of the <em>
      control</em> qubit, and the second parameter (<c>j</c>) represents the index of the <em>target</em>
    qubit.</p>

