  <section xml:id="qiskit-measuring" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Measuring Qubits in Qiskit</title>
    <p> Adding all of our favorite gates is only one part of building meaningful quantum circuits;
      once we have built our circuit, it only makes sense to <em>measure</em> the result of our
      circuit. In Qiskit, this is done with the <c>measure_all()</c> function. This measures the state of each of
      the qubits in our circuit and saves it to <em>classical bits</em> in the circuit <mdash />
      this is how we can measure our qubits and read their value! Let's check out an example: </p>

    <listing xml:id="qiskit-measure">
      <title>Measuring in Qiskit</title>
      <program xml:id="qiskit-measure-program" interactive="activecode" language="python3">
        <code>
          from qiskit import QuantumCircuit

          circuit1 = QuantumCircuit(2)
          circuit1.x(1)
          circuit1.cx(1, 0)
          circuit1.cx(0, 1)

          circuit1.measure_all()

          print(circuit1.draw())
        </code>
      </program>
    </listing>

    <p>All right, we've told our quantum circuit to measure our qubits and save the results! If you
      look closely at the output, we can see that a new <c>meas: 2/</c> double-line is present at the bottom
      of our circuit. This represents 2 <em>classical bits</em>, which are used to store the result
      of measuring our qubits. Additionally, after our gates, you should see two boxes with an <c>M</c>
      in each of them, with a double-line connecting to our classical bits. In quantum circuits, a
      single line represents quantum information, and a double line represents <em>classical
      information</em>. Finally, you can see a little <c>0</c> and <c>1</c> near the measurement
      connection, which indicates the index of the classical bits where the result is stored! We'll
      explore this more in future chapters. </p>
  </section>

</section>
